<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-449-960  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 449 960.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 29 1989 n1170 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hacking survey results.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collins, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A survey of 540 United Kingdom computer programmers and executivesrevealed that 137 admitted to having hacked into computer systems,with only 11 percent ever having been found out.andP;  The largestgroup of hackers worked in the banking and finance industries, andthe largest job orientation was in systems programming.andP;  42percent of the respondents were aware of internal attempts and 15percent of external attempts to penetrate their own organization'ssystems, with 42 percent of the incidents damaging data.andP;  The UKdoes not currently have criminal laws against hacking, but thegovernment is considering such legislation.andP;  Only 19 percent ofthe surveyed professionals did not think that hacking was an issuefor government regulation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications TappingAccess RightsComputer CrimesSurveyComputer IndustryUnited KingdomAttitudeImpact Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphcharttable.andO;Caption:   What is the main business, product or services of your company,organizaton? (graph)How much did the incident cost your company in financial terms?andO;(chart)Have you ever hacked a system yourself? (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>